<H1>Gary M. Gardner, Professor and Department Head</H1> 
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC ="gardner.gif"><P>

University of Minnesota, Department of Horticultural science, 305 Alderman Hall, 1970 Folwell Ave.,St. Paul, MN 55108; Telephone:  612-624-3606; E-Mail: ggardner@maroon.tc.umn.edu; Fax:  612-624-4941.<P>

Ph.D., Harvard University, 1972. <P>

Dr. Gardner's research interests are primarily in two areas of plant growth and development: environmental aspects of phytochrome physiology and plant hormone receptors.  He is interested in the broad question of the mode-of-action of plant
hormones, but his specific research will focus on the receptor for N-1 naphthylphthalamic acid and other inhibitors of auxin transport.  His long-term goal is to understand the role that this plasma membrane protein plays in normal developmental processes.  His phytochrome research will attempt to identify settings in which manipulation of phytochrome relationships can result in practical agricultural benefit, such as the control of flowering in greenhouse crops.  In this way, research on the role of phytochrome in the natural environment can be extended to the role of
phytochrome in the managed environment.  Dr. Gardner is a member of the graduate faculty in horticulture and plant biological sciences.<P>

<H2>Classes Taught</H2>
<A HREF="hort8041.htm">Hort8041</A>.  Discussions in Administrative Organization. <P>

<H2>Selected References</H2><P>

Gardner, G. and M.A. Graceffo.  1982.  The use of a computerized spectroradiometer to predict phytochrome photoequilibria under polychromatic irradiation.  Photochem. Photobiol. 36: 349-354.<P>

Bures, M.G., C. Black-Schaefer and G. Gardner. 1991. The discovery of novel auxin transport inhibitors by molecular modeling and three-dimensional pattern analysis. J. Computer-Aided Molecular Design 5:323-334.<P>

Kleier, D.A. and G. Gardner. In Press, 1992.  Quantitative structure-activity relationships: adding value to herbicide bioassays. In: J.C. Streibig and P.Kudsk, (eds.), Herbicide Bioassays, CRC Press, Boca Raton.<P>

