<H2>Potato Genetics and Breeding</H2><P>

Assistant Professor, 12-month, tenure
track, beginning January 1, 1997, or as soon as possible thereafter.
Department of Horticultural Science, University of Minnesota.<P>

Responsibilities<P>

Research (70%):
The successful candidate will be expected to conduct research on the
genetics of pest and disease resistance and other traits that are important
in sustainable potato production systems and provide leadership for a
potato cultivar improvement program.  Outstanding candidates will have
research strength in one or more of the following areas:  quantitative
genetics; breeding for stress, pest or disease resistance; or plant molecular
biology.  Research should focus on areas of plant genetics that will
facilitate the development of pest and disease resistant potato germplasm
and cultivars.  The faculty member will be expected to continue strong
collaborative efforts with plant breeders and other researchers located on
the St. Paul Campus and at Branch Experiment Stations throughout the
state.  The faculty member will also be expected to collaborate with
scientists in neighboring states in potato research that will benefit the
upper midwest.  The successful candidate must possess the ability to work
effectively with clientele groups and will be expected to attend and
participate in industry meetings and field days. <P>

Teaching (30%):
The faculty member will be expected to teach an upper level
undergraduate course in sustainable vegetable production and at least one
graduate level course in plant genetics or breeding and advise
undergraduate and graduate students in Horticulture and Plant Breeding. 
The faculty member will also be expected to participate in the Sustainable
Agriculture Graduate Minor.<P>

<H4>Qualifications</H4>

<H5>Academic</H5>
     Minimum:  Ph.D. in horticulture, genetics, plant breeding or
               related discipline with demonstrated expertise in
               plant genetics by date of appointment. <P>

     Desired:  Graduate-level course work in plant quantitative
               genetics, plant pathology, entomology, and
               molecular biology, including the use of molecular
               markers in quantitative genetics and plant breeding.
     
<H5>Experience</H5>
     Desired:  Dissertation or post-doctoral experience in plant
               quantitative genetics, plant breeding, and molecular
               biology, including the use of molecular markers in
               quantitative genetics and plant breeding. 
               Experience in potato breeding or production. 
               Demonstrated willingness to conduct collaborative
               research.  Demonstrated effectiveness in oral and
               written communication, and teaching.
 
Application Procedures<P>

Application materials must be received by September 30, 1996. 
Applicants must send a curriculum vitae, a statement of teaching and
research interests as related to this position, and the names, addresses, and
telephone numbers of three references to:<P>

 Chair, Potato Genetics SearchCommittee<P>
  Department of Horticultural Science<P>
  University of Minnesota<P>
  305 Alderman Hall<P>
  St. Paul, MN  55108<P>

THE UNIVERSITY OF MINNESOTA IS AN EQUAL OPPORTUNITY
EDUCATOR AND EMPLOYER AND SPECIFICALLY INVITES AND
ENCOURAGES APPLICATIONS FROM WOMEN AND MINORITIES.<P>
<P>
