<H2>Graduate Degree Programs</H2>

<A HREF="openra.htm">Read about Open RA Funding for new graduate students.</A><P>


The Department of Horticultural Science at the University of Minnesota offers the following graduate degree programs:<P>

Master of Science
Doctor of Philosophy
<A HREF="#masterofag">Master of Agriculture</A><P>

These degree programs prepare you for a professional career in teaching, research, extension, and domestic or international industry.  Because our degree programs are
interdisciplinary in scope and many of our faculty members are also members of other University graduate programs, we can offer you flexibility in composing a
program that meets your particular goals. In addition to<A HREF="#hort"> horticulture</A>, the<A HREF="#plantbreeding"> plant breeding</A> and <A HREF="#pbs">plant biological sciences </A>graduate programs are popular as majors or
minors for many students in the Department of Horticultural Science.<P>
<P>

MASTER OF SCIENCE AND DOCTOR OF PHILOSOPHY GRADUATE PROGRAMS<P>

<A NAME="hort">Horticulture</a><P>

Emphasis in both the master's and doctoral degree programs is placed on production, genetic improvement, use, and environmental impact of the crop or crop
production system.  As a student majoring in horticulture, you may focus on food, woody ornamental, floriculture, or turf crops in your studies.  Subject matter may range
from cold hardiness of perennial plants to stand establishment of vegetable crops using physiologic, genetic, or breeding techniques.  Research is conducted
in field, greenhouse, growth chamber, and laboratory environments and covers various aspects of whole plants and functions of their components.  These components
range from the structural study of flowers or roots to the subcellular analysis of biological systems.<P>

<A NAME="pbs">Plant Biological Sciences</a><P>

All aspects of the basic biology of both higher and lower plants are encompassed by the plant biological sciences program.  The objectives of the program are to provide
1) an integrated framework and cognitive structure for understanding plant biology, 2) skills for the synthesis of information and recognition of significant problems that
can be researched, and 3) capabilities for independent scholarship.  Examples of areas in which you can specialize include the following:  cell and molecular biology, plant physiology, plant structure diversity and development, ecology, systematic, and evolution.<P>

<A NAME="plantbreeding">Plant Breeding</a><P>

Plant breeding is an interdisciplinary field of study taught by faculty in our department and the Departments of Agronomy and Plant Genetics, Forest Resources, Plant
Biology, and Genetics and Cell Biology.  This program prepares you for research and teaching positions in universities, government agencies, private industry or
international agricultural agencies. Within this field of study you may concentrate on plant breeding or plant genetics.  Courses and research in plant breeding addresses principles, procedures, and methodologies relating to improvement of yield, quality,
and plant resistance to diseases and pests.  Courses in plant genetics include classical plant genetics, quantitative genetics, physiological and biochemical genetics, and
genetic methodologies such as cell and tissue culture techniques.<P>

Requirements:  The master of science degree is offered under two plans:  Plan A and Plan B.  A minimum of 44 quarter credits are required under both plans, including a
minimum of 20 quarter credits in the major field and 8 quarter credits in one or more related fields outside the major.  Under Plan A, 16 thesis credits are required to
meet the 44-credit minimum.  Under Plan B, remaining credits are completed through course work agreed upon by you and your adviser.  The master's program generally
takes two years to complete.<P>

The doctor of philosophy degree is granted in recognition  of superior knowledge in your field as demonstrated through examinations and preparation of a thesis.  The
doctoral program generally takes three to four years to complete.<P>

The master of science and doctoral degree programs are administered through our department.  For more information regarding requirements, please see the
Graduate School Bulletin.<P>
<P>

<A NAME="masterofag">Master of Agriculture</a><P>

This program emphasizes the application and management of science and technology or technical communications. The focus on application and management differs from the research orientation of the master of science degree.  Advanced professional competence is developed through an individual program of study in a field or combination of fields in agricultural and related sciences.<P>

This program requires a minimum of 45 quarter credits, 27 of which must be completed in residence.  This degree generally takes two years to complete and is usually
considered terminal.  If you plan to pursue a doctoral degree in the future, you should apply for the master of science degree program.<P>

Admission requirements for the master of agriculture degree program include completion of a bachelor's degree in a related subject and preferably two years' 
professional experience in the field.  If your undergraduate grade point average is 2.8 or less, you may be required to complete additional course work prior to
beginning the degree program.<P>

The master of agriculture is a professional degree program administered by the Department. Although it is an instructional program at the graduate level, it is not part of the University's Graduate School. For more information and application materials, please contact <A HREF="luby.htm">Dr. James Luby</A> 305 Alderman, University of Minnesota, St. Paul, MN 55108, telephone:  612/624-5300.  <P>

<I>To <A HREF="crslist.htm">Course List</A></I><P>
<I>To <A HREF="faclist.htm">Department Faculty</A> </I><P>
