<H1>BACHELOR OF SCIENCE DEGREE emphasizing  HORTICULTURE</H1>  at the
                                      UNIVERSITY OF MINNESOTA
 <IMG ALIGN=top SRC ="kobra.gif"><P>
The College of Agriculture and the Department of Horticultural Science offer
you several areas of study from which to choose:<P>

        <UL>
<LI>  <A HREF="#environhort">Environmental Horticulture</A>
<LI>          <A HREF="#cshfp">Crops, Soils and Horticultural Food Production</A>
<LI>          <A HREF="#aim">Agricultural Industries and Marketing</A>
<LI>          <A HREF="#sa">Science in Agriculture</A><P>
</UL>

<H2>ANIMAL AND PLANT SYSTEMS:</H2> This major prepares students to work as managers and technical advisers for animal and plant production systems.  Students majoring in animal and plant systems select an area of emphasis.  <P>

<H3><A NAME="environhort">Environmental Horticulture</a></H3> is an area of emphasis within the Animal and Plant Systems major.  When you choose Environmental Horticulture, you build from a strong science and business based curriculum to specific managerial and technical coursework.  Two sequences are available in the Environmental Horticulture emphasis.<P>

<H4>Landscape, Nursery and Turf</H4>:    
        Opportunities are almost limitless in this sequence that includes the design, production, implementation and maintenance of a variety of landscape plants.<P>

<H4>Floriculture</H4>:  
         Careers in greenhouse production and sales lead in this sequence that also includes garden center and flower shop management.  <P>

<H3><A NAME="cshfp">Crops, Soils & Horticulture Food Production</a></H3> is another area of emphasis within the Animal and Plant Systems major.  This emphasis stresses the breeding and production of horticultural field crops, vegetables and fruits. Careers include those involved in production, marketing, processing and regulation of
horticultural food crops.<P>

<H2><A NAME="aim">AGRICULTURAL INDUSTRIES AND MARKETING</a></H2>:  This major prepares students for positions in the manufacturing, assembly, distribution and processing of agriculture goods and services.  Horticulture is one of five emphases
that students may select to add industry specifics to this broad-based curriculum. Agricultural Industries and Marketing stresses basic and agricultural sciences as well as business methods and economic analysis.<P>

<H2><A NAME="sa">SCIENCE IN AGRICULTURE</a></H2>: Students in this major may choose one area of emphasis such as Horticulture, or several different disciplines to develop their own program.  A strong curriculum in biological and physical sciences and mathematics prepares students for graduate studies.  It also prepares students for
technical and research positions in industry, universities or government.<P>

Our Horticulture Department has lots to offer the undergraduate:<P>

<UL>
<LI>  A top-notch faculty and staff with wide-ranging areas of expertise.
<LI>  Over $20,000 in undergraduate scholarships awarded annually.
<LI>  Excellent facilities including laboratories, greenhouses.
<LI>  Landscape Arboretum and  Horticulture Research Center.
<LI>  Enthusiastic, friendly students.
<LI>  Opportunities for hands-on experience.
<LI>  Internships in your chosen field.
<LI>  Horticulture Club for student service,  learning, and fun.<P>

</UL>
For more information on these and other horticultural careers, please contact us:
 
       Department of Horticultural Science
               1970 Folwell Avenue
                305 Alderman Hall
             University of Minnesota
               St. Paul, MN 55108
                  612-624-4242
         kuype001@maroon.tc.umn.edu<P>

