<TITLE>University of Minnesota Landscape Arboretum</TITLE>
<H1>University of Minnesota Landscape Arboretum</H1><P>
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC ="snybld2.gif"><P>

Gather your thoughts among beautiful display gardens.  Read up on a particular interest in the Andersen Horticultural Library.  Visit the Meyer-Deats Conservatory to see exotic plants from around the worlds.  Enjoy an outdoor picnic or home-made lunch in the Tearoom.  Shop for a unique gift.  Gain new gardening insights.  <A HREF="arbspcal.htm">Special events</A> are happening all year long.  Come and enjoy a unique learning environment!<P>
Hours:     Open 361 days a year; Admission fee; members are free. Grounds open year round  8:00 a.m. to sunset each day.  Building hours and facility hours vary by season.<P>
Location:  9 miles west of  I 494 on State Highway 5 in Chanhassen, about a 40-minute drive southwest from downtown Minneapolis.   <P>
<B>For more information:  (612) 443-2460,  FAX (612)443-2521 or write Minnesota Landscape Arboretum 3675 Arboretum Drive, P.O. Box 39, Chanhassen, MN  55317</B><P>
<P>  

<B>Purpose</B>:  The mission of the Minnesota Landscape Arboretum, as part of the University of Minnesota, is to provide a community and a national resource for horticultural and environmental information, research and public education;  to develop and evaluate plants and horticultural practices for cold climates; and to inspire and delight all visitors with quality plants in well-designed and maintained displays, collections, model landscapes, and conservation areas.<P>

<B>Gardens and Collections</B>:  The Arboretum maintains 21 display and specialty gardens, 60 generic collections, 5,000 species of plants, and 6 native environments on 935 acres.<P>
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC ="rockgard.gif">     <IMG ALIGN=top SRC ="perngard.gif"><P>

<B>Seisui Tei. "Garden of Pure Water"</B>, is a fine example of a traditional Japanese wet garden featuring Minnesota-hardy plants.  Koichi Kawana, the designer, was a nationally recognized landscape architect who developed the garden for contemplative viewing throughout the four seasons.<P>

<B>The Hosta Glade</B>, with more than 250 varities of this foliage shade plant, is one of the largest collection of hosta in a public garden in the United States.  Sugar maples canopy this green glade which borders the fern walk, making it the coolest summer spot in the Arboretum.<P>

<B>The Grace B. Dayton Wildflower Garden</B> features native plants of the deciduous woodlands and incudes Minnesota's state flower, the showy ladyslipper.  A population of the dwarf trout lily (<I>Erythronium propullens</I>), a plant listed on the federal endangered species list and found only in Minnesota, is preserved here.<P>

<B>The Palma J. Wilson Rose Garden</B> contains 150 varieties of hybrid roses and a large trellised collection of clematis in a setting enhanced by fountains and a gazebo.<P>

<B>The Woodland Azalea Garden </B>displays hardy azaleas, most of which were developed by the Arboretum, and woodland plants, such as native ferns and wildflowers suitable for Minnesota Gardens.<P>

<B>The Herb Gardens</B> feature specialty collections of culinary herbs appropriate for a home garden, a knot garden, a collection of fragrant herbs, a cloistered garden with medicinal herbs, a selection of herbs used as dyes, and a garden for small spaces featuring herbs.<P>

<B>A Home Demonstration Garden</B> are a collection of garden and yard settings which give the visitor an idea of what they might do in their own yard.

<B>Native Environments:</B> The Arboretum has preserved several native environments found on its diverse landscape.  These include:  Maple and basswood forests; Tamarack Bog; a recreated Prairie, Fields, Ponds and soon a reestablished sedge marsh.<P>

<B>Education:</B>  The Arboretum offers a wide range of educational programs for students, adults and horticulture professionals.  More than 30,000 children K-6 annually attend workshops at the Arboretum or participate in the visiting Plant-mobile programs.  The Arboretum's Andersen Horticultural Library has over 10,000 volumes on horticulture, several computerized data bases, a rare book collection and an extensive seed catalog collection that dates from 1844 to the present.<P>

<B>Research:</B>  The Horticulture Research Center (HRC), a part of the Arboretum established in 1908, is one of the few institutions in the wold that identifies, propagates, and breeds cold-hardy fruit and landscape plants.<P>

<B>Fruit Development Program:</B>  More than 80 varieties of apples, raspberries and strawberries have been developed and released by the HRC and are available to the public through the nursery industry.  Two-thirds of the apples grown in Minnesota are HRC hybrids.  Hardy blueberry and grape introductions have opened new commercial production possibilities.  Varieties of grapes in development will aid Minnesota's emerging wine industry.<P>

<B>Landscape Plant Program:</B>  The "Northern Lights" series of azaleas were developed at the Arboretum.  Continued development and evaluation of a number of new varieties of landscape plants, shrubs and trees has given nursery professionals, landscape architects and home gardeners a broader inventory of superior landscape plants, enabling them to develop more attractive and longer-lasting residential, community and commercial environments.<P>

<H2>Facilities:</H2>
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC ="snybld1.gif">   Snyder Building<P>

<B>Leon C. Snyder Education and Research Building</B>:  offices, classrooms, conservatory, library, tearoom and gift shop.<P>

<B>Children's Learning Center:</B>  classrooms, greenhouse, and outdoor children garden.<P>

<B>Research greenhouses and laboratories</B><P>

<B>Picnic shelters</B><P>

<H2>Interesting Facts:</H2><P>

Attendance:  About 200,000 visitors annually<P>

Membership:  12,000 members, 500 Auxiliary members, 500 volunteers<P>

Employees:  40 full time; 70 part time and seasonal<P>

Funding:   University of Minnesota-35 percent; Memberships and private contributions-35 percent; Earned income-30 percent<P>

Tours:     Walking, bus and tram tours, and self guided or guided May through mid-October<P>

More Information:<P>  
Lori Carsik, PR - carsi001@maroon.tc.umn.edu<P>
Peter Olin, Director - olin002@maroon.tc.umn.edu<P>

