<H1>Mark L. Brenner, Professor</H1><P>

Ph.D., Michigan State University, 1970<P>

University of Minnesota, Department of Horticultural Science, 324 Alderman Hall, 1970 Folwell Ave., St. Paul, MN  55108; Telephone: 612-624-4735; E-mail: brenner@mailbox.mail.umn.edu; Fax:  612-624-4941.<P>

Dr. Brenner has taught courses on regulation of plant growth, methods for plant hormone analysis, and differentiation and plant development.  He conducts research on the role of endogenous plant growth substances in coordinately controlled processes.  Specific projects focus on regulation of partitioning and fruit set using soybean and corn plants as model systems.  Additional projects concern ABA metabolism, gibberellin biosynthesis and include a collaborative project on the regulation of gene expression in developing corn endosperm tissue.  Dr. Brenner has been actively involved in the development of physico-chemical analysis procedures for plant growth substances and has a laboratory uniquely equipped for such research.<P>

He has written review articles for Encyclopedia of Plant Physiology and Annual Review of Plant Physiology.  Dr. Brenner is a member of the horticulture and plant biological sciences graduate faculty, the Plant Molecular Genetics Institute, and the Plant Biology Department in the College of Biological Sciences.  He is Associate Vice President
for Research & Associate Dean of Graduate School.<P>
<P>


<H2>Selected References</H2><P>

Brenner, M.L. 1987. The role of hormones in photosynthetic partitioning and seed filling. In: P.J. Davies (ed.),  Plant Hormones and Their Role in Plant Growth.  Marinus Nijhoff, The Hague. pp. 474-493.<P>

Schussler, J.R., M.L. Brenner and W.A. Brun. 1991. Relationship of endogenous ABA to sucrose level and seed  growth rate of soybeans. Plant Physiol. 96:1308-1313.<P>

Ozga, J.A., M.L. Brenner and D.M. Reinecke. 1992. Seed effects on gibberellin metabolism in pea pericarp. Plant Physiol. 100:88-94.<P>

