<H1>Wesley P. Hackett, Professor</H1>
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC ="hackett.gif"><P>

University of Minnesota, Department of Horticultural Science, 252 Alderman Hall, 1970 Folwell Ave., St. Paul, MN  55108; Telephone:  612-624-9212; E-Mail:  hacke003@maroon.tc.umn.edu; Fax:  612-624-4941.<P>

Ph.D., University of California, Davis, 1962.<P>

Dr. Hackett teaches courses in plant growth regulation and development.  His research focuses on woody plant developmental physiology with emphasis on juvenility as it relates to adventitious root and bud initiation, somatic embryogenesis, and precocious flowering. He investigates phenylpropanoid and flavonoid metabolism in relation to root morphogenesis and juvenility.<P>

Dr. Hackett has published articles in horticultural, botanical, and plant physiological journals; has authored comprehensive reviews in the Encyclopedia of Plant Physiology and Horticultural Reviews; and is a contributor to the Handbook of Flowering.  He holds the Bailey Endowed Chair in Environmental Horticulture and has received research awards from the American Association of Nurserymen and American Society for Horticultural Science. He serves as an associate editor for several scientific journals.<P>

Dr. Hackett is a member of the graduate faculty in horticulture and plant biological sciences and is on the faculty of the Plant Biology Department in the College of Biological Sciences.<P>
<P>

<H2>Classes Taught</H2>
<A HREF="hort5040.htm">Hort 5040</A>.  Advanced Plant Growth Regulation<P>

<H2>Selected References</H2><P>

Wallerstein, I. and W.P. Hackett. 1989. Inflorescence induction and initiation in Hedera helix L. Israel J. Botany 38:71-83.<P>

Murray, J.R. and W.P. Hackett. 1991.  Dihydroflavonol reductase activity in relation to differential anthocyanin  accumulation in juvenile and mature phase Hedera helix L. Plant Physiol. 97:343-351.<P>

Geneve, R.L., M. Mokhtari and W.P. Hackett.  1991. Adventitious root initiation in reciprocally grafted leaf cuttings from the juvenile and mature phase of Hedera helix L.   J. Expt. Bot. 42:65-69.<P>

