<H1>Dr. Emily E. Hoover, Associate Professor</H1> <P>

<IMG ALIGN=top SRC ="hoover.gif"><P>

University of Minnesota, Department of Horticultural Science, 160 Alderman Hall, 1970 Folwell Ave., St. Paul, MN  55108; Telephone: 612-624-6220; E-Mail:  hoove001@maroon.tc.umn.edu;  Fax:  612-624-4941.<P>

Ph.D., University of Minnesota, 1982.  <P>

Dr. Hoover teaches undergraduate and graduate courses in general biology, growth regulation of horticultural plants, fruit production, and teaching techniques and is in charge of educational programming for commercial fruit growers in Minnesota.  Her research has focused primarily on evaluation of winter hardiness and winter protection/adaptation to enhance profitability, efficiency, and sustainability of fruit cropping systems.  Areas of emphasis include using apple rootstocks to increase
efficiency of apple cropping systems, utilizing grape training systems to improve winter survival, and surveying primocane fruiting red raspberries for adaptation to Minnesota conditions.  Investigations into the mechanism of cold acclimation in grape and grape isozyme banding patterns have been conducted.  Integrated pest management systems (IPM) for apples and berry crops are being adapted from models developed in eastern states.  She is a member of the horticulture graduate faculty.<P>
<P>

<H2>Courses Taught</H2>  <P>

Biology 1009:  General Biology<P>
<A HREF="hort5031.htm">Hort 5031</A>  Temperature Fruit Production.  <P>
<A HREF="hort8000.htm">Hort 8000</A>.  Supervised Teaching Experience n Horticulture.  
 <P>

<H2>Selected References</H2><P>

Hoover, E., J. Luby, D. Bedford and M. Pritts. 1988. Vegetative and reproductive yield components of primocane-fruiting red raspberries. J. Amer. Soc. Hort. Sci. 113:824-826.<P>

Fennell, A. and E. Hoover. 1990. Influence of photoperiod on growth, bud dormancy, and cold acclimation in V.  labruscana and V. riparia.  J. Amer. Soc. Hort. Sci. 116(2):270-273.<P>

Pomper, K., E. Hoover, P. Ascher. 1992. DNA content of Phaseolus coccineus X P. vulgaris suspensors.  Sex.  Plant Reprod. 5:146-150.<P>

