<H1>Alan G. Smith, Associate  Professor</H1><P>

<IMG ALIGN=top SRC ="smith.gif"><P>

University of Minnesota, Department of Horticultural Science, 356 Alderman Hall, 1970 Folwell Ave., St. Paul, MN  55108; Telephone: 612-624-9290; E-Mail:  alan@molbio.cbs.umn.edu<P>

Ph.D., University of Florida, 1985.<P>

Dr. Smith is interested in the physiology and molecular genetics of plant development.  His approach to plant development is to use flowers as a system to study cell differentiation and organ morphogenesis.  A first step toward understanding gene expression during flower production is the isolation of molecular clones of genes which are expressed only in flowers.  The clones are used in experiments to determine the function of genes and the mechanisms which regulate their expression.  These
analyses involve contemporary methods in molecular biology to define the temporal and spatial expression patterns of these genes as well as transformation of engineered genes into plants to manipulate flower morphogenesis.  Effects of specific changes in the regulatory or functional domains of a gene can be directly measured by
introduction of the altered gene into plants.  Mutants which affect the fertility or morphology of the flower are used in combination with the cloned genes to study abnormal flower development.  Results from these experiments will be used to develop a data base of the genes involved with flowering and their interactions.  Dr. Smith is a graduate faculty member of the horticulture and plant biological sciences program and is a member of Plant Molecular Genetics Institute.<P>

<H2>Courses Taught</H2>
<UL>
<LI> <A HREF="hort3004.htm">Hort 3004</A>. Applications of Plant Biotechnology
<LI> <A HREF="hort8061.htm">Hort 8061</A>.  Discussions in Plant Reproductive Biology. 
<LI> <A HREF="hort8066.htm">Hort 8066</A>. Discussions in Horticulture Research. <P>

</UL><P>

<H2>Selected References</H2><P>

Smith, A.G., C.S. Gasser, K.A. Budelier and R.T. Fraley. 1990.  Identification and characterization of stamen- and tapetal-specific genes from tomato. Mol. Gen. Genetics 222:9-16.<P>

Smith, A.G. 1992. Isolation and regulation of differentially expressed genes from flowers.  1993.  In:  B.R. Jordan (ed.), The Molecular Biology of Flowering, CAB International, Wallingford UK.  pp. 117-139<P>

Aguirre, P.J. and A.G. Smith.  1993.  Molecular characterization of a gene encoding a cysteine-rich protein preferentially expressed in anthers of Lycopersicon esculentum.  Plant Molec. Biol. 23:477-487.<P>

