<H1>Joseph R. Sowokinos, Professor</H1><P>

<IMG ALIGN=top SRC ="sowokino.gif"><P>

Address:  Red River Valley Potato Research Lab., Box 113, E. Grand Forks, MN  56721; Telephone:  218-773-2473; E-Mail:  None.<P>

Ph.D., University of North Dakota, 1968. <P>

Dr. Sowokinos, who specializes in enzyme isolation and characterization, conducts research involving metabolic regulation of carbohydrate metabolism in potato tubers.  Tissue culture (i.e., callus and suspension) cells are used in these studies along with field grown and stored tubers.  He has published articles on the partitioning of carbons and has developed a commercial method to measure the "chemical maturity" of potato tubers.  Dr. Sowokinos recently has been investigating the mechanism
of stress action (i.e., cold, heat, moisture, and handling) on the quality of potatoes used for processing.  He is currently interested in using molecular biology techniques to generate new potato plants with superior processing qualities and/or increased stress resistance.  Dr. Sowokinos is a member of the horticulture and plant biological sciences graduate faculty and is an adjunct professor in the Department of Horticulture and Forestry, North Dakota State University.  He is located at the USDA Potato Research Laboratory in East Grand Forks, Minnesota.<P>

<H2>Classes Taught</H2><P>
<P>

<H2>Selected References</H2><P>

Sowokinos, J.R., E.C. Lulai and J.A. Knoper. 1985.  Translucent sweetening in Kennebec potatoes (Solanum tuberosum L.) I. Alteration in amyloplast membrane integrity, enzyme activities, sugars and starch content. Plant Physiol. 78:489-494.<P>

Sowokinos, J.R., 1990. Stress-induced alterations in carbohydrate metabolism. In: Park, B. and M.E. Vayda,  (eds.), Molecular and Cellular Biology of the Potato.  CAB International, Wallingford, UK, pp. 137-158.<P>

Sowokinos, J.R. and J.L. Varns.  1992.  Induction of sucrose synthase in potato tissue culture: effect of carbon source and metabolic regulators on sink strength.  J. Plant Physiol. 139:672-679.<P>
