<H1>Mark S. Strefeler, Assistant Professor</H1><P>

<IMG ALIGN=top SRC ="strefele.gif"><P>

University of Minnesota, Department of Horticultural Science, 458 Alderman Hall, 1970 Folwell Ave., St. Paul, MN  55108; Telephone: 612-624-6701; E-Mail:  stref001@maroon.tc.umn.edu; Fax:  612-624-4941<P>

Ph.D., Cornell University, 1989.<P>

Dr. Strefeler teaches floral crop production and biotechnology courses.  He is interested in cultivar improvement of chrysanthemum, New Guinea Impatiens, cut roses, and fuchsia.  The focus of his breeding programs is the improvement of crop resistances to biotic and abiotic stresses.  The breeding program integrates classical breeding methods with the modern tools of molecular biology to develop superior cultivars and breeding lines.  Current work involves genetic engineering of
roses and African violets, breeding for heat and drought tolerance and the development of new floral crops from native plant species.  Dr. Strefeler is also interested in the collection and characterization of Impatiens spp. and Fuchsia spp. germplasm.  He is on the graduate faculty in the horticulture and plant breeding program.<P>

<H2>Classes Taught </H2><P>

<A HREF="hort5054.htm">Hort 5054</A>.  Commercial Floricultural Production Practices.<P>

<A HREF="hort5055.htm">Hort 5055</A>.  Commercial Floricultural Production Systems.  <P>

