<H1>David K. Wildung, Professor</H1><P>

<IMG ALIGN=top SRC ="wildung.gif"><P>

North Central Experiment Station, 1861 Highway 169E, Grand Rapids, MN  55744; Telephone:  218-327- 4490.  Fax: 218-327-4126<P>

Ph.D, University of Minnesota, 1972.  <P>

Dr. Wildung is located at the North Central Experiment Station in Grand Rapids, Minnesota, which is 175 miles north of St. Paul and has one of the shortest
growing seasons and harshest winter climates in the United States.  Current research focus is placed on development of cultural management systems for short season production and severe winter situations for blueberries, strawberries, and vegetable crops as well as extensive evaluation of breeding lines and cultivars for the extreme
climate.  The applied, field-oriented program involves research with small fruits, vegetables, potatoes, and ornamentals.  In addition to the research program, Dr. Wildung assists commercial growers and participates in extensive activities for commercial growers and home gardeners.  He is a member of the horticulture graduate
faculty.<P>

<H2>Selected References</H2><P>

Wildung, David K. and K.L. Sargent.  1989. The effect of snow depth on winter survival and productivity of Minnesota blueberries.  Acta Horticulturae 241:232-237.<P>

Wildung, D.K., K.L. Sargent and C. Rosen. 1990.  Soil acidification of Minnesota soils for blueberry production. Proc. of 6th North American Blueberry Research Extension Conference. pp. 94-98.<P>

Wildung, D.K., et al.  1989, 1990, 1991, 1992.  Minnesota vegetable cultivar trial results.  Midwestern Vegetable Variety Trial Reports. Dept. of Hort., Purdue University, Expt. Station Bulletin 557, 600, 627. In Press 25 to 30 pp. of Minn. results, annually.<P>

