<CENTER>
<H2>The Master Gardener Program in Minnesota </H2>
</center><P>

	The Master Gardener program in Minnesota is administered at the State Office in the Minnesota Landscape Arboretum, a part of the Department of Horticultural Science at the University of Minnesota. The State Office, along with the State Advisory Board, (consisting of 15 Master Gardeners representing all Districts in the state) selects four locations per year to conduct the Core Course or annual training of new Master Gardeners. These locations include the  Twin Cities and three outstate sites. The core training of interns consists of 48 classroom hours of training, similar at all sites, conducted by state specialists and extension educators. Volunteer requirements the 50 hours the first year and 25 hours annually thereafter.  A Pro-Hort option is 
offered at a higher price for participants who chose not to do the volunteer work.<P>

     Master Gardener training cost $40 in 1997 and Pro-Hort $250.  Eighty-three out of the 87 counties in Minnesota have Master Gardeners. As of 1996, there were 1509 active Master Gardeners in the state. Each fall participants turn in their hours tothe State Office and records are kept on total hours of service. In the spring of each year an Annual Conference is held and recognition is given to Master Gardeners who have volunteered for 10 years, 1000 hours, 15 years, and 2000 hours. Extension Educators or  Master Gardener Coordinators  in the 83 counties or within the cluster (multi-county grouping) are  responsible for local administration of the program.<P>  
	
     Typical contributions of MG's are answering phone inquiries concerning home 
horticulture, teaching classes, holding workshops, Home and Yard days, guiding and supervising community plantings and school gardens, teaching and judging 4-H horticulture projects or exhibits, writing newspaper columns and horticulture newsletters, holding plant clinics in garden centers, staffing county and state fair displays, etc. Many MG's are involved with horticulture therapy, teaching horticulture in hospitals, nursing homes, retirement centers for both children and adults. If  MG contact  5 people per hour, again a conservative estimate, 210,000 people 
were directly contacted by MG; at 10 people per hour (the State Fair average)  420,000 people were contacted.   <P>
	
     A new Core Course Text or MG Handbook was completed in 1994. The training material consists of extension publications and text . <P>
	
     For more information contact the State Master Gardener office, Minnesota Landscape Arboretum, 3675 Arboretum Dr. Chanhassen, MN 55317, phone 612-443-2460 ext 236, email <A HREF = "mailto: mmeyer@mes.umn.edu"> Dr. Mary Meyer at mmeyer@mes.umn.edu </a>
  <P>

</DOC>
