<H2>The Minnesota Extension Service Horticultural Specialization
</H2><P>

For the past four to five years the Minnesota Extension Service
(MES) has been divided into several program areas of which
Environmental Horticulture was one program.  Horticultural Food
Crops was in the Crops and Soils program.  In October of 1993,
MES was reorganized and Environmental Horticulture and
Horticultural Food Crops were combined into a unit called the
"Horticultural Specialization".  Although the former
Environmental Horticulture Program was active and viable, the
Hort Food Crops group was dominated by agronomic emphasis.  The
combined Horticulture Specialization allows a greater critical
mass in Horticulture to obtain visibility, program priorities
and service to the State of Minnesota.<P>
<P>
<P>

The purpose of the Horticulture Specialization is as follows:<P>

(1) Promote the technical, research-based advancement of
horticulture to the public and horticultural industries in an
environmentally responsible manner, including water quality and
pesticide safety, and in an economically sound manner. <P>

(2) Challenge and support the horticultural industry to operate in
an environmentally sound manner based on statistically sound
research.  Integrate disciplines such as soils, community
forestry, nutrition, plant pathology, entomology and wildlife in
the planning and implementation of these goals.  <P>

(3) Educate the public on the complexity, and the economic and social values of
horticulture.  <P>

(4) Foster horticultural business as it relates to economic development. <P>

(5) Educate citizens and volunteers (Master Gardeners) about the production and utilization of horticulture crops, services, and products.  <P>

(6) Provide staff development in horticulture for all clusters.  Serve as a liaison between
specialists and cluster needs.<P>
<P>
<P>

The Horticulture Specialization is accountable:<P>

To:
<UL>
<LI> University of Minnesota
<LI> Consumers
<LI> Professional industries, Production, Sales and Services
<LI> 	Environmental Horticulture
<LI> 	Horticultural Food Crops
<LI> Specific Governmental Units
<LI> Interdisciplineary Colleagues<P>

</UL><P>

For:	
<UL>
<LI> Credible Educational Informational and Resources
<LI> Recommendations for Sound Environmental Principles and Enhancement
<LI> Recommendations for High Quality, Safe Food Production
<LI> Effective Marketing and Delivery of Teaching, Recommending and Implementing
<LI> Environmental and Economical Horticultural Practices<P>

</UL><P>
<P>

The scope of the Horticulture Specialization includes the
provision of educational programming for commercial producers,
marketers, processors; for the providers of horticultural goods
and services, and for the consumers of those goods and services.
 Horticultural products include fruits, vegetables, nursery and
greenhouse plants, bedding plants and turf.  Providers of
horticultural services include retailers, wholesalers, landscape installation and maintenance, the recreation industry, public agenies, government agencies, environmental educators, volunteers, and people who serve in the realm of people/plant interaction.  The Horticulture Specialization is organized to include specific Working Groups within the Specialization.  Bert Swanson, Professor and State Nursery Management Specialist and Harvey Buchite, Anoka County Educator will provide overall leadership to the Specialization.  The working groups and
designated leaders are as follows:<P>
<P>

Working Group:                                                               Chairperson                                   
 
Commercial Horticultural Food Crops :   <A HREF="fritz.htm">Vince Fritz</A> - State
Vegetable Crop Specialist<P>

Consumer Horticulture:                               <A HREF="meyer.htm">Mary Meyer</A> - State Master Gardener Coordinator<P>

Commercial Environmental Horticulture:     Robert Mugaas - Hennepin County Educator<P>

Horticulture Computer Technology:		David Whiting - Ramsey County
Educator and Distance Education<P>

Horticulture Publications and Media:	      <A HREF="rosen.htm">Carl Rosen</A> - State Soil Scientist<P>
<P>

A complete research directory of the Horticulture Specialization
has been developed that lists the areas of expertise for each
member of the specialization.  It also provides information as
to their location and how to contact them.<P>

The Commercial Environmental Horticulture Working Group is in
the process of developing a Program Resource Directory which
will describe all on-going  projects and programs and the
personnel involved.<P>

The Horticulture Specialization meets quarterly to initiate,
integrate, coordinate and implement all Horticulture programs
for the Green Industry and for consumers in Minnesota.  A list
of Horticulture Emerging Trends for the specialization to
consider in future programming has been developed as indicated
on the next page.  Your comments on this list would be
appreciated.  In order to insure that this planning is on track
and that Environmental Horticulture does, in fact. have some
visibility, effectiveness and recognition throughout the MES,
the University and the State, and  Environmental Horticulture
Advisory Council was established.  The Advisory Council is
subsequently described in detail in two separate articles in
this document.<P>

Please direct any questions or comments about the Horticulture
Specialization to <A HREF="swanson.htm">Bert Swanson</A> or the Environmental Horticulture Advisory Council.<P>

