<body background = "fract1.jpg" >
<H2>Hort 3010.  Growing Plants Organically:  What It Means To Be "Green"</H2><P><P>

Welcome!  <P>

If you have made it this s far you have an interest in growing plants using less synthetic chemicals or you are interested in what it really means when advertisers or growers claim their products are "green".   You have come to the right place!<P>

This Fall we will explore these issues with an emphasis on the scientific, ethical, and legal basis for "organic cultivation".  Check out the tentative syllabus below.<P>
<P>

<H4>Tentative Syllabus</H4>	
	
<B>Week 1</B>:  Definition and discussion of terms: i.e. "organic", "sustainable"
Legal definitions and public consensus uses of terms.  History of "organic" versus "chemical" agriculture.<P>

<B>Week  2</B>:  Review of certification procedures for being classified "organic". Guest discussion leader from "Organic Growers and Buyers Organizations".
Choose research projects.<P>

<B>Week  3</B>:  Case studis on organic processes.<P>

<B>Week  4</B>:   Presentation and discussion of important topics not picked by students. Field trip.<P>

<B>Week  5</B>:  Presentation and discussion of important topics not picked by students.
	
<B>Week  6</B>:  Student presentations (progress reports),  Paper outlines due.<P>

<B>Week  7</B>:  Student presentations (progress reports)<P>

<B>Week  8</B>:  Student presentations (final reports)<P>

<B>Week  9</B>:  Student presentations  (final reports)<P>

<B>Week 10</B>:  Student presentations  (final reports),  Final paper due.
Wrap up,  conclusions,  flexible time.<P>
<P>

<H4>Possible student project areas</H4><P>

<UL>
<LI> Organic practices in your "favorite" crop.
<LI> The use of BT.
<LI> In depth of your local grocery store marketing of "organic".
<LI> Weed control.
<LI> House plants practices.
<LI> Breeding for organic culture.
<LI> Home vegetable garden practices
<LI> Legislative view of "organic"
<LI> Lawns and turf
<LI> University view of "organic"
<LI> Biodynamics					
<LI> Sludge
<LI> Manure<P>

</UL>
<H4>Grading:</H4>  <P>

Grades will be determined on class attendance and participation (30%),  oral report (30%) and final paper (40%).  <P>

Course style:  The course will stress oral and written communication skills.  Lectures will be few.  Discussion and student presentations will be emphasized.  Field trips, guest discussion leaders (hopefully farmers or policy makers in this area), and case studies will augment student lead discussions.<P>

   	
		
	<P>

</DOC>
