<head><title>
HORTICULTURE 5015 
RESTORATION AND RECLAMATION ECOLOGY</title></head>
<body>
<h3 align="center">HORTICULTURE 5015 </h3>
<h2 align="center">RESTORATION AND RECLAMATION ECOLOGY</h2>
<h3 align="center">COURSE INFORMATION</h3><hr size=10 noshade><br>

After you complete this course, you should have an understanding of the ecological concepts that are 
important for effective ecosystem restoration and have familiarity with practices used in successful 
restorations.  On Mondays and Wednesdays, throughout the quarter, you will learn about ecological 
concepts as they pertain to revegetation.  During the first half of the course, Friday sessions will focus 
on site selection, design and planting considerations for specific ecosystems.  During the second half 
of the quarter, we will visit restoration sites in the Twin Cities area. <hr size=2 noshade>

<h2>SCHEDULE:</h2>
This class meets on  Monday, Wednesday from 9:00-9:50 A.M. and Friday from 8:00 - 9:50 A.M.  
During the second half of the quarter, we will meet at field trip locations at 8:00 A.M. (unless indicated 
otherwise on the syllabus).<hr noshade>

<h2>INSTRUCTOR:</h2>
<A HREF="../galatowi.htm">Dr. Susan  Galatowitsch</A><br>
		260 Alderman (624-3242)<br>
		125F Architecture (626-7948)<br>
        email: <A HREF="mailto:galat001@maroon.tc.umn.edu">galat001@maroon.tc.umn.edu</A><br>
<br>
Office Hours:  10-11 A.M.  MW<hr noshade>

<h2>PREREQUISITES:</h2>
You should already have a general background in ecology and botany including one course in 
ecology and one in botany.  If you take this class without these pre-requisites, you will need to obtain 
a text on your deficient subject and refer to it as necessary during the quarter.<hr noshade>

<h2>READING ASSIGNMENTS:</h2>
Each student should purchase the <A HREF="5015read.htm">reading packet</A> for the course from Copies on 
Campus (St. Paul).   You will be assigned <A HREF="5015reqr.htm">required readings </A>in a variety of books 
and journals.  These readings will relate to the concepts we are covering in class either as a landmark  paper or 
as an interesting example.   I will assume you are familiar with these readings when I lecture and when you are 
tested.<hr noshade>

<h2>TECHNIQUE AND FIELD TRIP SESSIONS:</h2>  We are fortunate to have a number of guest instructors 
this quarter.  They bring a wealth of experience to the course.  Before each session, I will ask you to 
jot down a question related to their area of expertise that you hope they will address.  I will compile 
these questions for each guest to give them an idea of some of our interests in their topic.  The 
information covered in these sessions will be included in the course exams.<hr noshade>

<h2>OTHER INTERESTING OPPORTUNITIES:</h2>  It's spring - high season for restoration activity!  During 
the quarter there will likely be opportunities to assist in site preparation or planting on projects like Big 
Sandy Lake in Aitkin County (as well as others).  These are optional.<hr noshade>

<h2>RESTORATION CASES:</h2>  Documenting restoration activities is essential for improving the state of our 
understanding.  To that end, we will produce an electronic journal volume, <em><A HREF="rrr.htm">
Restoration and Reclamation Review</a></em>, that is a compilation of 
restoration case studies.  All students will write a 6-8 page (double-spaced, 11 point, Times-Roman) 
paper that describes a restoration or reclamation project of their choosing.  Each paper should include 
information on site location, the intended results and the motivation for the project, the interventions, 
assessments of success, and a critique of the project.  I will serve as editor of the volume meaning 
that I will ensure minimal redundancy between cases and will oversee reviews.  Each student will 
review  three papers.  Each student will revise their paper to address comments received from the 
three reviewers and myself.  Upon approval, you will submit your completed case on a 3.5 disk using 
a standard word-processing application.  I will be seeking several students to write synthetic overviews 
of sections of the journal issue (as prefaces).  These writers can use the overview as their final exam 
score.  I will make the volume available to you the week of final exams.  
 Your score will be based on:<p> 
		
		 	First draft:	40% (my review of content, grammar & style)<br>
			Reviews:	15% (completeness of three reviews)<br>
			Final Draft: 	45% (content, grammar & style).<hr noshade>

<h2>GRADING AND EXAMS:</h2>
Two exams covering lecture material, and a paper will be used to evaluate the extent of your 
understanding of restoration and reclamation ecology.  Make-up exams will be granted by special 
permission only and only for extenuating circumstances that were discussed with me prior to the 
exam.<p>

A  grade of incomplete (I) will be assigned when part of the course requirements are missing at the 
end of the quarter, unless in my opinion there is no possibility they can be completed to give a grade 
above an N.  The work must be turned in by the first week of the Summer Session to remove the I, 
except in unusual circumstances and after negotiation with me.<p>

Evaluation:<p>	

	30%	Paper<br>
   	30%	Mid-term exam<br>
	40%	Final exam<br>
	100	Total<br><hr noshade>


