<DOCOLDNO>IA053-000892-B014-311</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.dis.mil:80/automatd.htm 207.132.241.10 19970111232914 text/html 6293
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Communications/1.1
Date: Sunday, 12-Jan-97 02:24:31 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 03-Oct-96 16:38:29 GMT
Content-length: 6103
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>DIS Infrastructure</title>
<meta name="Author" content="Matt Martelli">
<meta name="Project" content="home">
<meta name="Server" content="Internet">
<meta name="Date" content="10-3-96">
<link rel="previous" href="overview.htm">
</HEAD>
<BODY background="/images/texture.gif">

<center><H3>DEFENSE INVESTIGATIVE SERVICE</H3>
<H3>Automated Infrastructure Architecture</H3></center>
<HR>
<BR>
<ul>
<P>The primary means that DIS supports these functional tasks is undergoing
a major redesign effort. DIS is developing a new system called the Case
Control Management System (CCMS). The CCMS will:</P>

<UL>
<LI>Use the computer to store and view information that was previously
stored on paper or microfiche, thus greatly reducing our dependence on
printed documentation;</LI>

<LI>Use the computer to automate repetitive tasks, thus reducing the time
necessary for the Personnel Investigations Center in Baltimore to process
each investigation;</LI>

<LI>Use the computer and telecommunications to reduce mail delay by replacing
mailed paper with transmitted electronic documents.</LI>
</UL>

<P>The CCMS Architectural Description is:</P>

<P><img src="/images/ccm.gif" width="100%">

<UL>
<P>This graphic shows the major activities that DIS uses in
conducting its day-to-day business. The following paragraphs explain what
this graphic represents:</P>
</UL>

<H3>Customers:</H3>

<UL>
<LI>DoD agencies who need investigations as a basis to grant clearances
or access to classified information or facilities.</LI>

<LI>DoD and other Federal or local agencies who need to review DIS investigative
files.</LI>

<LI>Contractors who process or store classified information. Contractors
may use DIS for investigations to get their workers clearances as well
as being participants in the Industrial Security Program with DIS's industrial
security representatives.</LI>
</UL>

<H3>EPSQ:</H3>

<UL>
<P>The EPSQ (Electronic Personnel Security Questionnaire) is an automated
way for subjects to enter their background information, submit it to security
officers and then have it transmitted directly to DIS for inclusion in
the DIS Corporate Database. This function also includes DoD Form 562 for
contractor security officers to submit personnel security changes electronically
to DIS. To learn more about the EPSQ go to our <A HREF="projects/epsq/index.htm">EPSQ
home page</A></P>
</UL>

<H3>National Agencies:</H3>

<UL>
<P>National Agencies are those government institutions that provide information
from their respective databases on subjects of DIS investigations. For
all subjects this includes the FBI and a check of the Defense Clearance
and Investigations Index (DCII).  To learn more about the DCII go to our
 <A HREF="projects/dcii/index.htm">DCII home page</A></P>
</UL>

<H3>Field Office Operations:</H3>

<UL>
<P>Each field office assigns leads (or investigative requirements) to an
agent. The agent electronically downloads these lead assignments and produces
lead results on a laptop computer. The agent then uploads the lead result
to the corporate database. It may or may not be reviewed by the field office
chief before it is included as a final lead result. The field office will
be a true CCMS user and be able to check the progress of a lead or an investigation
that it is assigned.</P>
</UL>

<H3>Case Closing:</H3>

<UL>
<P>As part of the case management process, the last lead will initiate
an action to close an investigation. If there is no derogatory information,
the CCMS will close the case automatically. However, some cases that have
other than totally favorable results must be reviewed by a case analyst
and closed manually.</P>
</UL>

<H3>Investigation Submission:</H3>

<UL>
<P>Although not shown on the graphic, the final step is for an adjudication
agency to make a clearance determination based upon the results of the
DIS investigation. These agencies can review the case on-line as a CCMS
user, or through an Internet Browser application.</P>
</UL>

<H3>Industrial Security Program:</H3>

<UL>
<P>The Industrial Security Program (ISP) and its Key Management Personnel
(KMP) program interface directly with the CCMS. Before a facility can be
cleared to process or store classified information, KMPs are required to
be cleared commensurate to the level of the facility clearance. Changes
in KMP status, or facility status must be reflected in the CCMS. These
will occur through &quot;triggers&quot; in the corporate database.</P>
</UL>

<H3>Files Management</H3>

<UL>
<P>Under the CCMS, files management will drastically change. Our goal is
to eliminate the use of microfiche to store images. We will be using optical
media for all new paper documents that we receive and will convert existing
microfiche files to optical images when they are requested. In the future,
these files, as well as on-going investigations, will be maintained electronically
and only put on physical media when the requester's special situation (such
as Freedom of Information Act inquiries) warrants a paper response.</P>
</UL>

<H3>Workflow Management</H3>

<UL>
<P>The heart of the CCMS will be a Workflow Management package. This package
will allow us to change the flow of an electronic document interactively
through a Windows interface without redesigning the application. The use
of a commercial Workflow package means that many actions that previously
had to programmed from the start, such as processing flows, user access
authorizations, investigation statistical information and work assignment,
are already developed and ready to be included into the final CCMS application
software.</P>
</UL>
</ul>
<br>
<hr>
<p><a href="overview.htm"><img src="/images/back.gif" alt="back arrow" align=bottom border=0 width=40 height=40></a> Go back to the DIS Overview page</p>
<hr>
<address>Author: Matt Martelli<br>
Revised: 3 October 1996 </address>
