<html>

<head>
<title>Common Data Structure Documentation</title>
<meta name="Author" content="William Howard">
<meta name="Project" content="EPSQ">
<meta name="Server" content="Internet">
<meta name="Date" content="8-9-96">
<link rel="previous" href="index.htm">
</head>

<body background="/images/texture.gif">
<h1><center>Common Data Structure (CDS) Information</center></h1>
<hr>
<p><img src="/images/technic.gif" align=bottom width=54 height=54> The Utility section of the main EPSQ menu allows the user to load and unload data from a CDS format. We now 
have documentation available to assist the user in this in this process. The purpose of using this function would be to move 
EPSQ data from custom legacy systems to the EPSQ software.</p>
<p>The file available for downloading (CDS.EXE) contains three files. The CDS.DOC is the CDS Format User's Manual, 
formatted in Microsoft Word. The other two files (DBFSTRUC.TXT and TABLES.TXT) are ASCII files of the database 
structure and the lookup tables.</p>
<p><strong>WARNING:</strong> A sepearte EPSQ directory containing the SO version of the EPSQ software should be used solely for 
migrating legacy data into EPSQ. Otherwise, erroneous data may corrupt existing EPSQ data. The data from the CDS file is 
loaded into the EPSQ data files without checking for duplication. Data from this special CDS EPSQ directory may then be 
imported into the regular EPSQ SO edition, when you are sure the files are acceptable.</p>
<p>It is the sole responsibility of the custmoer to support the implementation of the CDS. The CDS may be subject to change 
with the release of EPSQ 2.0 in September 1996.</p>
<hr>
<h2>Download:</h2>
<p><img src="/images/ball_mag.gif" alt="*" align=bottom width=14 height=14> Common Data Structure (<a href="ftp://www.dis.mil/pub/projects/epsq/cds.exe">CDS</a>) documentation (200 K) </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="index.htm" target="body"><img src="/images/back.gif" alt="back arrow" align=bottom width=40 height=40></a> Go back to the EPSQ home page. </p>
