<html>

<head>
<title>Director for Investigations</title>
<meta name="Author" content="Matt Martelli">
<meta name="Project" content="home">
<meta name="Server" content="Internet">
<meta name="Date" content="10-15-96">
</head>

<body background="/images/texture.gif">
<br>
<center><IMG SRC="/images/rharding.gif" ALT="[Picture]" BORDER=5></center>
<br>
<center><H2>                RENÉ DAVIS-HARDING</H2>
<H3>                    DEPUTY DIRECTOR OF INVESTIGATIONS<br>
                       DEFENSE INVESTIGATIVE SERVICE</h3></center>
	

<p>Ms. Davis-Harding was appointed Deputy Director for Investigations,
Defense Investigative Service on May 13, 1996.   She also serves as
the functional manager for the 1,200-person cadre of investigators
and polygraph examiners in the conduct of personnel security
investigations for the Department of Defense, elements of the
Intelligence Community, warfighting commands and other Federal
Government agencies.



<p>Ms. Davis-Harding has gained a reputation for excellence as the chief
trouble-shooter and problem-solver on a wide range of the most difficult
(new, highly complex or controversial) counterintelligence and security
matters. Among her commendations are three Commanders Awards for Exceptional
Achievement, the Republic of Korea Civilian Service Medal, the Director
Community Management Staff Exceptional Performance Award, and the Director
of Central Intelligence Meritorious Unit Award.  Ms. Davis-Harding has more
than 23 years experience in a succession of progressively responsible overseas,
field, and staff positions within the Navy, Army, and the Office of the Secretary
of Defense, to include:

<p>
<dl>
<dt> Director for Security Programs, 1994-1996.
  <dd>Ms. Davis-Harding was appointed to the SES on April 30, 1995, as the Director
      for Security Programs, Office of the Assistant Secretary of Defense (Command,
      Control, Communications, and Intelligence).  Her position was created to fuse
      DoD security policy, procedures, and oversight of classification management, 
      personnel, industrial, physical, nuclear, operations security, port and overflight
      security, the polygraph program, as well as security countermeasures education and
      training.

<p><dt>Professional Staff, Joint SecDef-DCI Security Commission, 1993-1994.
  <dd>Ms. Davis-Harding was chosen as one of a select group to staff the prominent senior
      civilian and government officials serving on the Joint Security Commission, which
      continues to reshape the federal governments security system through its report,
      Redefining Security, dated February 1994.  Ms. Davis-Harding acted as the
      Commissions focal point for its inquiries into security policy for special access
      programs, as well as the classification management, technology protection, industrial
      security and counterintelligence areas.
 
<p><dt> Information Security Specialist, 1982-1987;
<dt> Intelligence Operations Specialist, 1991-1993; Army Headquarters, Deputy Chief of Staff for Intelligence.
  <dd>Ms. Davis-Harding served two tours on the Army Staff.  She was selected by the Director
      of the Army Staff to act as his executive secretary for the Stilwell Commission General
      Officer Steering Committee, worked personally with the Assistant Secretary of the Army in
      developing the first Army policy on foreign ownership, control, and influence of defense
      contractors, served within the Counterintelligence Division as the focal point for
      intelligence special access programs, devised the first policy for counterintelligence
      support to special access programs, and established and funded the Army's Acquisition
      Systems Protection Program for protecting leading-edge technology.

<p><dt>Chief of Security Branch, Joint Intelligence, United States Forces Korea (USFK), Republic of Korea, 1988-1990.
  <dd>Ms. Davis-Harding led the military and civilian Branch responsible for advising the
      Commander-in-Chief on classification management, personnel, information, physical,
      industrial, technical security, and foreign disclosure policy issues. She exercised
      staff supervision over the TSCM, TEMPEST, counter-SIGINT and polygraph assets in theater,
      and successfully steered security for the first special access program deployed to Korea.

</dl>
<p>Ms Davis-Harding is a native of Washington, DC and currently resides in
Arlington, Virginia.  She is married to BG Robert A. Harding, an Army officer,
and they have two daughters, Michelle (29) and Anita (20).<br>

<p><a href="../dinv.htm"><img src="/images/back.gif" alt="back arrow" align=bottom border=0 width=40 height=40></a> Go back to the Investigations page.</p>
<hr>
<address>Author: Matt Martelli<br>
Revised: 11 October 1996 </address>
</body>

</html>




