<P>
<B>CI Incident Log</B>
<P>
he NACIC solicits information on incidents reported
by US companies. Most useful are incidents that reflect specific
methods, circumstances, and general geographic areas or types
of organizations. 
<P>
<B>Laptop Vanishes in East Asian Hotel</B>
<P>
Below is a sanitized version of a US company's loss
of proprietary information in March 1996.
<P>
A major US consumer products company suffered a possible
loss of proprietary information as a result of a theft in East
Asia. A laptop computer containing sales data, market estimates,
and strategic business plans for one of its business units was
stolen from a hotel conference room during a lunch break. Hotel
staff-under the supervision of a company employee who was preparing
remarks for the next presentation-cleaned the room for the afternoon
session. The employee did not continuously guard the computer
and discovered the loss shortly before the session reconvened.
<H3>In the News</H3>
<P>
<B>Navy Sailor Charged With Espionage</B>
<P>
On 22 April 1996, Machinist's Mate First Class Kurt
G. Lessenthien, 29-an instructor at the Navy Nuclear Power School
in Orlando, Florida- was arrested by the FBI and accused of trying
to sell top secret information to an FBI undercover agent. The
investigation, run jointly by the FBI and the Naval Criminal Investigative
Service, was initiated after Lessenthien made contact with the
Russian Embassy in Washington, DC- allegedly offering classified
documents. The documents that Lessenthien attempted to pass related
to nuclear submarine operations; the most sensitive was classified
top secret.
<P>
<B>Wiretap Epidemic Possibly Sanctioned by Paris</B>
<P>
According to a 28 March 1996 Reuter report, about
100,000 French telephone lines are illegally tapped each year,
and state agencies may be behind much of the eavesdropping. Citing
information from an annual report by the independent National
Commission for the Control for Security Interceptions, the press
article states that the wiretapping restrictions imposed on government
officials may be prompting them to hire private firms to do their
illegal bugging.
<P>
According to the press article, magistrates can only
approve legal wiretaps in criminal cases or to protect national
security, prevent terrorist threats, or safeguard essential scientific
or economic information. The article stated that the magistrates
okayed about 3,000 legal phone taps in France in 1995, mainly
for national security or antiterrorism purposes. They also authorized
an additional 11,300 wiretaps in support of criminal cases. 
<P>
<B>Swiss Expel Russian Diplomat for Espionage</B>
<P>
According to a 9 April 1996 Reuter report, Switzerland
ordered a Russian diplomat to leave the country for spying. A
Justice and Police Ministry statement said the first secretary
from the Russian Embassy in Berne was caught in the act of espionage
by federal officials and police in Zurich. No further details
were provided.
<P>
<B>CIA Spy May Leave Prison for Halfway House</B>
<P>
According to a 8 April Chicago Tribune report, William
Kampiles-the former CIA clerk who stole a classified manual on
America's KH-11 spy satellite and sold it to the Soviets in Athens
for $3,000-may be released as early as June 1996 because prisoners
awaiting parole routinely are assigned to halfway houses six months
ahead of time. He has applied for a transfer from his Rochester,
Minnesota, prison to the Chicago area.
<P>
<B>CI Capsules</B>
<P>
Regional Seminar Update
<P>
The Industrial Security Awareness Council of Chicago
(ISAC/C) along with the Windy City Illinois Roost Chapter of the
Association of Old Crows and the NACIC will sponsor a regional
seminar at the Northrop Grumman Corporation in Rolling Meadows,
Illinois, on 19-20 June 1996. NACIC Director Michael J. Waguespack
will address the seminar on the issue of economic espionage. Among
the speakers will be Lynn Mattice-Director, Corporate Security,
Whirlpool Corporation-and a host of government officials, including
a State Department expert on China and the Far East. The seminar
theme is ''Protecting International Sales: Do you? Can you? Should
you?'' The coordinator for this event is John Conmy, Northrop
Grumman, at (847) 259-9600, Ext. 6200.
<P>
The Gateway ISAC, the Heartland Chapter of National
Classification Management Society (NCMS), and NACIC will sponsor
a regional seminar at McDonnell Douglas Headquarters in St. Louis,
Missouri, on 21-22 August 1996. Dr. James P. Chandler-President,
National Intellectual Property Law Institute-will deliver the
keynote address. Other speakers will be from the Federal Bureau
of Investigation, Martin Marietta Corporation, the National Security
Agency, the Defense Investigative Service, and the Monsanto Company.
The seminar theme is ''Protect Technology, Safeguard Business-Secure
America.'' The point of contact for registration and other information
is Mr. Bill Giese at (314) 232-3348.
<P>
The NACIC regional seminar coordinators have received
several calls from you on the west coast, chiding us a bit for
our neglect in not exhibiting a more ''westward ho'' attitude
when selecting locations for future seminars. Honestly, we had
no intentions of slighting our ''west coast cousins'' and hope
to remedy this situation with a seminar in Los Angeles in December
1996, and perhaps one in the northwest in the spring of 1997.
To provide comments or suggestions on these two proposed seminars,
please contact the NACIC's Community Training Branch at (703)
874-4122.<BR>

<P>
<B>CI News &amp; Developments</B>
<P>
National Counterintelligence Center
<P>
Room 3W01 - NHB
<P>
Washington, DC 20505<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<P>
<h6>Customer input is crucial for this publication to
provide the information and content required to help you and your
counterparts in government and industry. Please complete the following.
<p>
Personal Information
<P>
(name, title, orgn, address, phone)
<P>
Comments, Impressions, Topics of Interest<BR>
<BR>

<P>
1) ASIS-the largest private-sector organization for
security professionals with some 25,000 members worldwide-sponsors
surveys every two years in an attempt to quantify corporate information
loss and measure its impact on US companies. The March 1996 report
is the third of the series and included corporate data from 1993,
1994, and the first seven months of 1995. The copyrighted 1996
ASIS report was prepared by Richard J. Heffernan, CCP, and Dan
T. Swartwood, OCP. Inquiries should be directed to ASIS offices
at 1655 North Fort Myer Drive, Suite 1200, Arlington, VA 22209-3198.
<BR>
<P>
2) For complete text of the ASIS report, contact ASIS
directly (see previous footnote).</h6><br>
