<BR>
Subject: [A] CI Needs for Industry<BR>
<HR>
<P>
<h2>Survey Of The Counterintelligence Needs Of Private Industry
</h2>
<br><br>
<P>
<B>Introduction</B>
<P>
Foreign intelligence activities against U.S. industry are serious
concerns in today's global marketplace, threatening U.S. national
and economic security. Millions of U.S. industry dollars are lost
annually through the theft of information by foreign governments.
Similarly, technological advancements, market shares, and customer
lists of U.S. firms are stolen each year by foreign companies
seeking to gain an unfair advantage. Proactive efforts by corporate
management can protect their proprietary information from the
illicit activities of foreign governments and companies thereby
mitigating the extent of these losses. 
<P>
The National Counterintelligence Center (NACIC) and the U.S. Department
of State's Overseas Security Advisory Council (OSAC) are specifically
mandated to support the U.S. public and private sectors with counterintelligence
information and were directed in 1994 by the National Security
Council to identify ways to enhance this relationship. The NACIC
was established on August 1, 1994 by Presidential Directive as
an interagency organization to manage national-level counterintelligence
activities for the U.S. Government. The OSAC is a joint partnership
between the U.S. Department of State's Bureau of Diplomatic Security
and the U.S. private sector to share information on overseas security
issues.<BR>
<P>
<I><B>Methodology</B></I>
<P>
 In recent years, corporate America has become increasingly vociferous
about receiving more counterintelligence information from the
intelligence community. A priority of the NACIC was to ascertain
how counterintelligence information is currently used by private
industry and to identify future needs for such information. A
NACIC-OSAC survey questionnaire about the economic espionage threat
from foreign intelligence and security services sought to clarify
the CI informational needs of private industry. The questions
were derived from discussions with several corporate security
managers in the fall of 1994 and with OSAC's Executive Council.
The survey focused on current use and availability of threat information,
past practices of sharing with the U.S. Government suspected incidents
involving foreign intelligence targeting of U.S. companies, and
ways to improve the flow of information in the future.
<P>
In December 1994, OSAC mailed 1400 surveys to the corporate security
managers of their affiliate members as well as featuring the survey
on the OSAC electronic bulletin board. Only 173 responses (12.4%)
were received by February 1995; although a 12% return is average
for these types of surveys, it is less of a return than was expected
from an audience which seemed highly motivated concerning the
subject matter. (See Appendix for a copy of the survey questionnaire
which contains the raw response data.)<BR>
<P>
<B>Key Findings</B>
<P>
 The following conclusions are given from the viewpoint of all
173 respondents as well as from the viewpoints of the two primary
subset groups within that total -- 68 companies which hold classified
government contracts and 105 companies which do not. As appropriate,
the responses were also analyzed by general industry groups: defense/energy
contractors, manufacturing, industrial/engineering, service sector,
and financial corporations. The first section of the report presents
graphically the responses to the questionnaire and the second
section makes some comparisons and discusses the conclusions.
In general, the survey findings highlight that:
<P>
&#183; the mechanisms in place for the exchange and sharing of
counterintelligence (CI) information need energizing and improvement,
and
<P>
&#183; more emphasis is required for awareness training to heighten
employee sensitivities to the information collection tactics of
foreign governments and the potential for losses through industrial
theft and other illicit practices by foreign interests.
<P>
These results should not be construed as a statistically accurate
survey of the counterintelligence concerns of all U.S. private
industry, but rather a snapshot of companies concerned with foreign
economic intelligence gathering directed at them.
<P>
<B>The Survey in Detail -- What Respondents Said</B>
<P>
The survey questions are given below in the order in which they
were presented to the OSAC membership along with a brief statement
to put the question in context. The graphs represent the percentages
given for each response; <B>many of the questions allowed for
multiple responses.<BR>
</B>
<P>
Question 1: How frequently does your senior management use threat
information about foreign government activities and intentions
in making corporate policy decisions? 
<P>
This was asked as a baseline question to discover if senior executives
of U.S. corporations are currently using counterintelligence information
to make risk management decisions.<BR>
<P>
Question 2: How is that information currently obtained?
<P>
(From what entity.)<BR>
<P>
This question gave insight into how private industry obtains counterintelligence
information.<BR>
<P>
Question 3: During the past year, has your company expended resources
to safeguard against foreign government attacks to your:
<P>
This question helped to define the current willingness of corporate
executives to expend company dollars to safeguard their technology,
facilities, and employees from thefts or losses.<BR>
<P>
Question 4: Does your company have a counterintelligence awareness
training program for employees?
<P>
This question was designed to learn if corporate America is active
in ensuring that their employees are aware of counterintelligence
concerns; specifically whether corporations had formal training
programs.<BR>
<P>
Question 5: How useful are the following types of information
for convincing senior management of the foreign intelligence threat?
(Chart indicates rating as Highly Useful.)
<P>
This was an attempt to ascertain what types of counterintelligence
information would be needed by corporate security managers to
help them define the foreign intelligence threat to their senior
management.<BR>
<P>
Question 6: Indicate the number of instances you suspect foreign
governments have targeted your company during the past year domestically
and overseas.
<P>
Although this was a small sampling, it provided some insight into
the scope of the foreign collection threat as recalled by private
industry.<BR>
<P>
Question 7: In those instances where you suspect foreign government
targeting of your company, what was targeted?
<P>
This question was designed to identify which areas of corporate
operations or assets are believed targeted, and therefore cause
the most concern for the private sector.<BR>
<P>
Question 8: How often did your company share information about
these incidents with the U.S. Government?
<P>
This was asked to gain an understanding of the level of communication
and current flow of valuable information from private industry
to the federal government.<BR>
<P>
Question 9: To what degree would senior management be willing
to allow the U.S. Government to use specific information on collection
incidents by foreign governments if your company's name was not
revealed?
<P>
Providing briefings is always more beneficial if the briefer has
specific examples with which the audience can relate. This question
inquired about the degree to which private industry would share
its experiences so that others could benefit.<BR>
<P>
Question 10: Would senior management be willing to share the dollar
value of the loss?
<P>
What makes more of an impact to corporate executives than hearing
about incidents that would affect the company's profits? This
question also gauged the level at which private industry would
share its experiences in terms of monetary impact.<BR>
<P>
Question 11: How would you prefer to <I><B>forward</B></I> information
on collection incidents by foreign governments to the counterintelligence
community? Through:
<P>
This was a question to determine if there was a clear preference
by private industry for how it would want to report information
to the U.S. Government.<BR>
<P>
Question 12: How would you prefer to <I><B>receive</B></I> threat
information?
<P>
From: (what entity.)<BR>
<P>
By: (what form.)
<P>
This two-part question was identifying how private industry wanted
to receive information from the federal government, through which
entities and in what form. This would assist the outreach programs
in understanding industry's needs.<BR>
<P>
Question 13: What is the classification level for threat information
that your senior management would prefer to receive on a routine
basis? (Chart indicates rating as Most Prefer.)
<P>
This question attempted to identify the classification level of
information corporate security managers would find most usable
for discussing the foreign intelligence threat with their senior
executives or in awareness briefings with employees.<BR>
<P>
Question 14: Does your company routinely have classified contracts
with the U.S. Government?
<P>
This question was intended to help clarify the previous question;
those corporations that do not have classified contracts may not
be able to receive classified threat information and may not fully
understand the government's classification system.<BR>
<P>
Question 15: How great a problem are foreign government attempts
to steal your company's proprietary information compared with
other factors (e.g., legitimate competition, employee turnover)
that adversely affect your company's profit margin? (Chart rates
5 as a greater problem and 1 as a lesser problem.)
<P>
This question focused on the extent to which losses of proprietary
information by foreign collection efforts are comparable to other
economic threats to U.S. private industry.
<P>
<B>Discussing the Results --</B> <B>&quot;Where Do We Go From
Here?&quot;</B>
<P>
Foreign intelligence collection efforts are growing throughout
the world; it only makes sense that the United States, as an economic
and technological superpower, is the target of choice to steal
proprietary information or technology secrets. To compete against
foreign markets, U.S. private industry and its employees need
to be informed of the collection methods and targeting priorities
of foreign governments and corporations.
<P>
Albeit a small return, the survey did provide some insight for
the intelligence community on the areas of interest to private
industry. As indicated, corporations' highest priority is information
on foreign government targeting of their proprietary information,
employees, telecommunications or facilities. They also would like
to receive incident information to bolster their threat briefings
and information on foreign intelligence services' general methods
and intentions. They prefer meetings or briefings and regularly
issued threat publications. The survey further identified several
areas that need attention such as the process of information flow
to and from private industry and the lack of awareness training
within U.S. industries.<BR>
<P>
<B>Private Industry's Use and Access to Counterintelligence Information</B>
<HR>
<P>
<I><B>CI Use and Availability.</B></I> Of the 173 U.S. corporations
that responded, 68% frequently use threat information about foreign
government activities and intentions in making corporate policy
decisions. For corporations that have classified contracts, 69%
frequently use threat information in their decisions and 67% of
the companies without classified contracts frequently use CI information.
The biggest users are the financial community (80%) and the industrial/engineering
corporations (79%).
<P>
Why do only two-thirds of the U.S. corporations use CI information?
One explanation may be the lack of access to such information.
Thirty-two percent of the corporations indicated that they do
not have contact with federal CI representatives. Even of those
U.S. corporations that have classified government contracts, 19%
have no relationship with a federal government representative
for obtaining counterintelligence information and 31% seldom use
threat information in their decision making. In addition, 40%
of the corporations without classified contracts have no relationship
with the federal government. This may indicate that the U.S. Government
and corporate security managers are falling short in sharing counterintelligence
information to safeguard U.S. industries.
<P>
<I><B>Classifications.</B></I> Another explanation may be the
perceived value of the information from the federal government.
The intelligence community has held the assumption that private
industry does not want unclassified information, that corporations
will continually ask instead for secret government data because
that must be the best information. The survey, however, indicated
that 53% of the corporations <B>most preferred</B> unclassified
material. The <B>least preferred</B> material was top secret government
information. The fact that there was also a substantial interest
in classified information indicates private industry officials
want to be sure they are receiving relevant, high quality threat
information. This illustrates the dilemma that continues to confound
the intelligence community: how to provide detailed information
while still protecting sensitive sources or operational activities.
One respondent cautioned the intelligence community not to tell
private industry that they have &quot;highly classified and sensitive
intelligence information only to [reveal information that] was
published in an unclassified news magazine months earlier.&quot;
<P>
<I><B>Process Issues.</B></I> The fact that one third of the respondents
have no contact whatsoever with U.S. intelligence representatives
may be an indication that the interaction between the private
sector and the Intelligence Community for accessing and reporting
counterintelligence information needs to be strengthened. Although
there are many U.S. Government agencies that provide threat information
to private industry, more emphasis needs to be placed on these
federal outreach programs which require active agency support
to ensure their credibility and viability within private industry.
<P>
There are several outreach programs already in existence. The
FBI runs the Development of Espionage, Counterintelligence, and
Counterterrorism Awareness (DECA) Program, the Defense Investigative
Service's (DIS) counterintelligence office has a program for the
DoD contractor community, and the State Department coordinates
the OSAC program with its member affiliates. Each reaches out
to U.S. corporations for giving and receiving threat information.
These processes, already in place and affirmed by the majority
of survey respondents, need to be invigorated and expanded to
spread counterintelligence information into more of the private
sector and back to the intelligence community. One example of
a new initiative that is taking place is the NACIC's team effort
with OSAC. OSAC already has a process for providing notices of
crime and terrorism directed at U.S. companies operating overseas
through their electronic bulletin board. The NACIC intends to
work with OSAC to expand the use of their bulletin board to include
counterintelligence reporting.<BR>
<P>
<B>Suspected Targeting and Resource Expenditures of 74 Corporations
<BR>
</B>
<P>
<I><B>Targeting. </B></I>Seventy-four companies reported 446 incidents
where suspected targeting by foreign governments had taken place
against their companies domestically or overseas in 1994. In the
overwhelming majority of these incidents, the primary goal for
foreign intelligence targeting was corporate proprietary information.
However, while these 74 corporations reported suspected targeting
of their companies in 1994, only 16% felt that those losses were
through foreign government theft attempts, suggesting the remainder
stemmed from industrial theft and other illicit activities. Interestingly,
45 out of 95 corporations with technologies on the National Critical
Technologies List reported 237 of the suspected incidents indicating
that slightly more than half of the targeting was against U.S.
critical information.
<P>
Fortunately, the 74 corporations that suspected targeting have
also expended resources toward safeguarding proprietary information,
employees, facilities, and telecommunication systems so steps
are being taken to protect their business assets.
<P>
However, only 58% of the 74 companies reported the incidents to
the U.S. Government. This lack of reporting hinders the government's
capability to provide accurate counterintelligence information
back to U.S. industry and its subsequent usage in corporate decisionmaking.
Hence, communication between private industry and the intelligence
community needs to be more open in both directions.
<P>
<I><B>Interactive Communication.</B></I> Are security managers
willing to give incident information for use by other corporations?
Corporations with classified contracts indicated more of a willingness
to share incident information (91%) than corporations without
classified contracts (75%). <BR>
<P>
<B>Sharing Information With the U.S. Government</B>
<P>
However, when it came to revealing a dollar value associated with
the loss, only 66% of corporations with classified contracts and
47% of corporations without classified contracts indicated that
they would be willing to share that information. The financial
corporations were more willing than any other industry group to
give both incident information and the dollar value lost. This
response is not surprising since private industry has other factors
-- a board of directors, stockholders, the stock market -- which
makes them hesitant to reveal profit margin information. Nonetheless,
such monetary impact data can represent the &quot;smoking gun&quot;
so essential to selling the value of CI awareness training and
threat briefing programs.
<P>
Once information on foreign modus operandi is collected, up-to-date
analytical reports can be produced and distributed so that all
industries can benefit. As identified, the FBI has a DECA coordinator
in each of their field offices to provide general or specific
threat information in meetings or briefings with corporate security
managers or senior executives. The CIA's National Resources Division
has provided briefings on foreign intelligence services' methods
directly to various corporations. The Defense Intelligence Service
and other DoD military components also actively support the defense
contractor community with threat analyses and briefings. OSAC
has a number of Country Councils overseas and has created a Committee
for the Protection of Information and Technology to exchange economic
threat information.
<P>
As for publications, the DECA program periodically publishes foreign
intelligence threat information in <I>DECA Notes. </I>The NACIC
is producing a national <I>Counterintelligence News and Developments</I>
publication as another method for getting information to the private
sector. Although these are not quarterly reports as requested
by survey respondents, such products are focused in the right
direction and should be used as the framework for a positive exchange
of threat information. The NACIC has also begun a project to catalogue
current counterintelligence products for private industry use.
These individual programs and publications all strive to support
private industry but a more coordinated effort to share information
must be developed for the future.
<P>
<I><B>Reporting to the Government.</B></I> In order to be more
understanding of the changing threat, private industry must be
encouraged to provide feedback on methods and tactics that are
being used against them. Eighty-one percent of total respondents
indicated that they would be willing to give information to the
U.S. Government. Where corporations have contact with multiple
federal agencies, a standardized reporting format might be more
effective.
<P>
It is important to ensure that, when CI incident information is
reported by industry, the process for collecting and analyzing
the data and producing threat assessments is a coordinated effort
by the federal government. For the future, the NACIC is exploring
the feasibility of developing a centralized database on foreign
government targeting of U.S. information, sanitized to remove
the corporation's identity, in order to provide a more complete
and accurate picture of the foreign intelligence services who
are actively stealing corporate secrets.
<P>
<I><B>Counterintelligence Awareness Training Programs. </B></I>Less
than half of the respondents to the survey acknowledged having
awareness training programs. This is an area that needs a coherent
national counterintelligence &quot;outreach program&quot; to support
threat awareness for U.S. industry. Out of the total responses,
43% indicated that their corporations have counterintelligence
awareness training programs for employees. For those corporations
that do not have classified contracts, just 25% have training
for employees. Conversely, of the 68 companies that have classified
contracts, 72% have CI training programs in place. When broken
down by industry, the defense/energy contractor respondents reported
that most (83%) of their corporations have awareness programs.
However, only 13% of the financial corporations, 32% of industrial/engineering
corporations, 39% of manufacturing corporations, and 46% of service
corporations have employee awareness programs. Further, less than
half of those corporations whose technologies appear on the Government's
National Critical Technologies List provide awareness training.
<P>
This does not bode well for protecting corporate intellectual
property <I><B>since employees are a company's weakest link in
protecting sensitive information</B></I>. The findings from a
&quot;Technology Theft and Proprietary Protection Assessment&quot;
Survey conducted by the American Society for Industrial Security
(ASIS) in 1992 indicated &quot;over 50% of attempts to misappropriate
proprietary information involve employees or ex-employees and
when you add in vendors, suppliers and sub-contractors, the total
is almost 70%.&quot; 
<P>
<B>View of Awareness Training and the Foreign Threat<BR>
</B>
<P>
The loss of sensitive or proprietary information through employee
turnover or disgruntlement is apparently perceived as a more worrisome
concern to U.S. industry than thefts by foreign governments. Sixty-three
percent of respondents indicated that foreign government attempts
to steal company proprietary information were a lesser problem
when compared with other factors affecting the profit margin.
However, since intellectual property thefts can be a covert activity,
designed to elude detection, many corporations may not realize
that foreign intelligence services have targeted them. If employees
aren't made aware of the tactics used by foreign intelligence
services to obtain sensitive economic information, intellectual
property may be lost unnoticed resulting in financial drain on
the corporation.
<P>
Some effort is underway to provide better awareness to the private
sector. The NACIC has created an interagency Awareness Working
Group for evaluating and coordinating the government's industrial
training programs and to design new programs. The State Department's
OSAC members have published <I>Guidelines for Protecting Business
Information Overseas</I> to provide specific ways for protecting
business information and raise levels of awareness. DECA coordinators
and DIS industrial security representatives assist corporate security
managers with awareness briefings and provide materials to private
industry. Corporate security managers have the responsibility
to obtain and institute these programs in the workplace. The more
employees are made aware of tactics employed by foreign governments
to acquire U.S. industrial and economic information, the greater
the chances that those tactics and activities may be recognized,
reported, and neutralized.
<P>
<B>Appendix</B>
